+{"id":"franken_numpy-fdz1","title":"[HIGH] cumsum/ptp/convolution conformance harnesses compare NumPy to itself","description":"Reviewer pass on the latest fnp-python native-wrapper commits found that the new subprocess-based conformance harnesses do not reliably exercise fnp_python.\n\nEvidence:\n- crates/fnp-python/tests/conformance_cumsum.rs:116-123 builds the NumPy oracle script and the rust_script from the same `import numpy as np; np.cumsum(...)` body. Axis and dtype cases repeat the same pattern at lines 163-172, 202-212, 286-293, 371-379, and 407-415.\n- crates/fnp-python/tests/conformance_ptp.rs:117-123 compares `np.ptp(...)` to the same `np.ptp(...)`; axis/dtype/nan cases repeat at lines 163-170, 199-209, 239-243, and 264-268.\n- crates/fnp-python/tests/conformance_convolution.rs only tries `fnp.convolve` in the full-mode test, then swallows every import/runtime failure and prints NumPy fallback at lines 107-123. The same/same-valid/correlate tests never import fnp_python at all and just run NumPy on both sides (for example lines 155-163, 194-202, 238-246, 277-285, 316-324).\n\nWhy this is HIGH:\nThese tests were committed with native cumsum/cumprod/ptp/convolution coverage claims, but they can stay green if fnp_python is missing, if the native fast path is never called, or if the wrapper regresses. That creates a false green signal on exactly the recent parity surface being reviewed.\n\nReproduction:\n1. Inspect the line ranges above; both commands passed to numpy_oracle are identical NumPy scripts, or the fnp_python path is wrapped in a catch-all fallback.\n2. Temporarily break `fn cumsum`, `fn cumprod`, or `fn ptp` in crates/fnp-python/src/lib.rs, then run `cargo test -p fnp-python --test conformance_cumsum` or `--test conformance_ptp`. The harness still exercises NumPy-only scripts instead of the PyO3 module.\n\nExpected fix:\nRewrite these harnesses to use the existing crates/fnp-python/tests/common/mod.rs helpers (`with_fnp_and_numpy`, `run_case`, `run_case_resolved`) or an equivalent embedded-PyO3 path that imports the in-process fnp_python module and compares it against NumPy without catch-all NumPy fallback. Add at least one negative-control assertion or structure that would fail if fnp_python.<function> is missing.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-29T00:48:31.843321121Z","created_by":"cod_2_reviewer","updated_at":"2026-04-29T00:48:31.843321121Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["conformance","fnp-python","review"]}
